      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;A world drowning in its own sin hosts a fledgling witch, who earns her keep by banishing the spirits of the past.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1265919-hazel-and-the-attic/chapter/1265921/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Hazel and the Attic&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;author's note: This story contains descriptions of &lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/133722/violet_velvet/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/33/ava_133722_1725238337.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/133722/violet_velvet/"&gt;Violet_Velvet&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt; abuse, transphobia and sadness.&lt;br /&gt;edit: I've waffled on the title, just gonna stick with the original.&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sanctuary Megacity &lt;br /&gt;20XX&lt;br /&gt;59 MSL&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Rain fell in a soft rhythm, pattering upon the paved streets as those dwelling in their lit homes slumbered. A thin fog clung to trees growing from the remains of derelict buildings, their swollen trunks drunk deep upon the bounty provided by the heavens. Only a few souls wandered these streets at night, some were desperate, others were seeking safety. One of these souls was driven.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The lone girl was covered in a large green rain jacket, her worn rain boots keeping the surrounding water out of her thick, woolen socks. A large black umbrella was contributing to keeping out the rain, and protecting her large satchel composed of brown leather. The client’s home was far out from the center of the main city, but Hazel didn’t mind walking out this far. She preferred the quiet solitude of the outskirts to the hustle and bustle of downtown.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She held up her phone, wrapped in a protective sheet of plastic, double-triple checking that she had gotten the address correct. 1340 Barrett Street. It was a small, unassuming two story home, the tile roof had fallen apart in a few places, though the gutter still did its best to handle the steady rain. The presence of a lawn and picket fence made it seem somewhat quaint, though the grass had long since overgrown and was covered in thick weeds.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Taking a few careful steps up the partially collapsed stairs, the girl extended a gloved hand, and knocked on the door. After a few seconds, a muffled voice on the other end came through the door.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes? Who is it?” The feminine voice asked, with no small amount of agitation and years behind it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It’s Hazel, you called me last week to help you out with your problem.” The girl answered flatly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the other end, the voice of Ms. Beatrice brightened at once. “Oh well why didn’t you say so? Come on in!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The door opened, and Hazel stepped into the home. It was a quaint little home, if one ignored the water leakages in the ceiling, and the plethora of overfull buckets that were collecting the rain. Ms. Beatrice had opted for a classic style of decor, and Hazel could spot several kitchen implements that would fetch a high price at an antique shop. The edge of Hazel’s head twinged with a headache as she stepped inside.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Something was here, she was certain of it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m so glad you could make it, I am at my wit’s end with that… that thing!” The old woman’s voice was tinged with sincerely felt annoyance, towards whatever was causing the problems in the attic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel nodded as she removed her coat, hanging it up on an open rack. Her outfit underneath was designed for comfort far more than style, as the turtleneck brown sweater kept out the cold, and her jeans just worked. A pair of round glasses complimented the shape of her face, and a scrunchie held her ruddy brown hair up in a ponytail. The only piece of jewelry she wore was a simple necklace with an onyx as its centerpiece. Lastly of note was the thick leather belt around her waist, sewn with several pockets that held her tools. Most prominent among the objects was a carefully carved stick that ended in a point, and a knife, bound in a leather sheathe.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I can’t say for certain what your problem is, but I will take a look and get to the bottom of it.” Hazel was certain of what the problem was already due to her earlier premonition, but she didn’t want to needlessly concern the old woman.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The old woman gave her a dubious look as she drunk in the girl’s somewhat modest appearance. “Are you quite certain you’re up for this?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel simply nodded her head. She was somewhat accustomed to that reaction, even if it still stung a little. “I am. I’ve been doing this for Ten years now.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Ten years… for someone as young as you?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She did wince at that. It was an odd profession for someone of twenty four years, but she’d had plenty of experience. Hazel kept her gaze fixed on Ms. Beatrice’s thin grey eyebrows, and mulled over a response. “It’s a living. We all do what we must to survive in these times.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Ms. Beatrice looked the girl up and down with a scrutinizing gaze and nodded her head. “Well, all right. I suppose you can give it a go. Can’t do any worse than the last guy I called in.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Even though Hazel knew that the address was meant to be neutral, a part of her couldn’t help but flinch even a little at being called “guy”. Did she suspect…?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The older woman led her upstairs, and along the railing until finally reaching a closed hatch on the ceiling that led into the attic. The headache that Hazel felt only grew more prominent the closer they were to the attic, and she once again wished she could have found Ibuprofen on her last shopping trip. Ms. Beatrice turned to address Hazel again, goosebumps visible on her bare arms.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“At first, I thought the noises were just part of the old structure, but they only grew louder with each passing day. About three months ago, I called in a guy to go up and check what was making that noise. I would go up myself, but I can’t climb on account of my knees you see.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel nodded her head. The woman didn’t have to justify her challenges, but she knew from experience that sometimes letting the client vent about it would help them. “I’m sorry to hear that ma’am.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Ms. Beatrice’s smile grew, and for a brief moment Hazel spotted a twinkle in her fading blue eyes. “Such good manners! Those are rare these days, why I remember-”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel cleared her throat and looked up at the hatch. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh yes yes, of course I suppose I should let you get on with it. But do consider visiting for a while with me after you’re done?” There was an edge of pleading to her voice, the desperate pleas of a lonely old woman.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I suppose, if I have the time.” She acquiesced with a slight sigh.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wonderful! I’ll be sure to bake some cookies for you dearie. Now, I’ll stop running my mouth and let you handle it. Though do be careful up there.” And with that, she departed downstairs, with a spring in her step.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel released a breath she didn’t realize was being held. Talking with the clients was always her least favorite part of the job. She’d rather be doing something, than talking with strangers. Around older people she felt especially skittish, she could never tell when one was about to drop the “S” word on her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Slapping her cheeks a few times, Hazel reached her gloved hand up to the hatch and pulled down on the string, bringing down the ladder. Reaching into her supplies, she retrieved the compact flashlight and began to ascend. The ladder creaked with every step of her boots, and for a brief moment she wondered if they might crack under her weight. Darkness surrounded her on all sides as she poked her head into the attic, and with no light sources available,  she flicked on the torch.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nothing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She shone the light all around her, but the attic was empty, devoid of any storage. Cautiously taking a few steps forward, Hazel fully entered the attic space and stepped further in. The only sound she could hear was the steady tinking of raindrops falling on the roof, and a few loose raindrops falling onto the flooring. Given the size of the house, the attic should only go back about fifty meters, but it seemed to stretch on endlessly in the darkness. There was no evidence of mice, rats, or other vermin that might be making the sounds that Ms. Beatrice was reporting.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She knew better though. Whatever was up here would not make its presence known immediately. Her hand unconsciously slid to the knife she kept sheathed on the back of her belt, fingering its pommel with her thumb. There would certainly be a trace of the presence, she just needed to find what was keeping it tethered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And then her boot made contact with something on the floor. Stopping in place, Hazel bent over to find a photo case, covered in a thick layer of dust that concealed the entire piece. Except for the middle aged man, standing prominently in the corner of the frame. Hazy shadows clung to the edge of the frame, despite the light of the torch. Hazel sighed as her worries were confirmed, having found the source of the problem. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Taking a deep breath before a plunge, she extended a shaky hand to touch the photo.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The attic hatch &lt;em&gt;slammed&lt;/em&gt; shut, and the &lt;strong&gt;darkness&lt;/strong&gt; swallowed her torch, leaving Hazel in pitch black. And then, inky shapes formed, their color deeper than their surroundings. They came together to form the hazy outline of a figure, its body defined by the contrast with the surrounding darkness.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And then, in a horrid, wheezing voice, it spoke.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“... &lt;em&gt;LeAve…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Hazel stood her ground, blinking nonchalantly as the spirit whispered its command. Just as she suspected, a restless spirit had taken up residence in the attic. A bead of sweat dripped from her brow, as her hand squeezed the knife’s pommel. Prepared as she was, there was always a risk when it came to spirits. She would have to be careful about this.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why do you linger here spirit?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The spirit wailed, its shriek splitting her ears, and even covering them up did little to prevent the horrid unearthly sounds it produced.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;LeAVE!!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;It shrieked once more, and Hazel fell to her knees, the sound reverberating deep into her skull and throughout her body. The wails were at just the right pitch to trigger her. Her hands scrambled about for something, anything that might help her and brushed up against the photo that lay on the ground.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Is… nngh, is it because of this?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The shrieking faltered, until finally the spirit went quiet. Hazel breathed in the mildewy air, and held her breath.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“... &lt;em&gt;fAmilY…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;The light of her torch returned on the photograph, the formerly faint shadows having formed into a tendril that connected to the wailing spirit. With a gentle hand, she wiped away the thick dust on the frame, revealing a woman and two young children, both boys. Warm nostalgia filled her body, followed by icy cold memories.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What happened to them?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The spirit made a quieter shriek, and Hazel watched in fascination as its hazy ‘head’ turned to the side, avoiding her gaze. She’d grown more accustomed to speaking with spirits, but this one in particular seemed averse to conversation. Luckily, she came prepared for that possibility.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She reached into her satchel, and retrieved a thermos full of liquid. Unscrewing the cap, she poured an aromatic tea she had prepared earlier into the cap. The spirit turned its ‘head’ back to face her, the aroma having settled it down.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;sMellS Nice…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Hazel did her best to keep a neutral expression, and blew on the tea, its soothing aroma suffusing the air around the spirit. “It’s Lavender Chamomile, with just a hint of Ginseng I prepared it myself at home.” While spirits could not partake of the beverage itself, they could still absorb its scent, and even in death, that had an effect.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She took a seat on the dusty floor, and looked up to the spirit, taking a long sip of her tea, and feeling the tension leave her body. “So… your family?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A long, breathy hiss came from the spirit, its sigh revealing decades of unresolved emotions. It remained around her, its gaze lingering on the picture in her hands. An inky black tendril extended to gently caress the woman in the image.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;bRenDa…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;It touched the two boys.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;jOhn… tiMothY…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;The spirit’s unearthly voice was tinged with deep regret that stirred Hazel’s heart to pang with empathy at its plight.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;bRenda… Left… tOOk thE boYs…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;She winced. Attempting to keep her own biases in check was difficult, as her mind wandered to a particular place at the mention of a father’s wife leaving with the children. But these circumstances might be different, and it was important to keep an open mind. “Why?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;tO protect tHe Boys… fRom… Me.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Hazel’s grip on the thermos tightened, as the anger shot through her body with the speed of a lightning bolt. Her preconceptions were dominating the thoughts in her mind. She wanted to say ‘Is it any wonder that she left then?’ The grip on her knife tightened, her eyes wandering towards the shadowy tether and she was sorely tempted to end this. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Spirits were people though, a fact that she was all too aware of. To kill it, would be to mark herself as a witch that solved problems through violence, instead of communication. No, she would not take that route. For the sake of cooperation, she would do her utmost to reach this spirit.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What… did you do?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;I… I…” &lt;/em&gt;The shrieking returned, and Hazel winced at the overstimulation, covering her ears once more with her mittened hands. The spirit’s temper tantrum was an occurrence she had grown increasingly accustomed to over time, and she knew that it would only be a matter of time until it ceased. However, its loud wailing was causing her immense pain, and she had to stop that at least.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I understand this is difficult, but if you don’t talk to me I can’t help you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The horrid wailing slowed once more, until it finally stopped altogether. An uncomfortable and heavy silence hung over them for a moment, until the spirit finally spoke again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;tiMoThy… said… he was a girl”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;The electric rush of anger returned, even stronger this time. This… this man was not deserving of her sympathy, or her understanding. He was a monster that inflicted horrible pain on his family, and the world would be better off if she just cut the tether right then and there.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And yet.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She could not stifle the empathy centers, as she recalled her own past, images flashing unbidden through her mind. Hazel couldn’t just banish this spirit, she felt a strong need to reach out, and make it understand where it had gone wrong. In a sense, even after his death, he was Still causing problems because of his own lack of empathy. And if no one ever showed him that empathy, then he would never know it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Even if he didn’t deserve her help, he deserved peace. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I… I understand.” She softly spoke, and the spirit craned its head in her direction. “I told my family that I wanted to be a girl, many years ago.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A heavy silence hung in the attic, save for the drops of rain. The girl and the spirit locked gazes, it was easier for Hazel when the spirits had no eyes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And then.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“... &lt;em&gt;wHy?”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel shrugged, and took another long swig of her tea, the hot liquid soothing her frayed nerves. She had committed to this route, and now she had to do her utmost to see it through to the end. “Because I wanted to. I wanted it, more than anything in the world. And because I pursued what I wanted, it cost me everything.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;... wAs it worth iT?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Hazel instinctually nodded. “Absolutely. I would do it again without regret. It certainly didn’t solve all my problems, but now I feel like someone who can tackle all those problems. Who can look in the mirror, and not loathe what I see.” She took another sip of the tea, her mouth dry. “It was extremely difficult to tell my birth family, I agonized over it for weeks, months… and years. And when I finally told them, they tossed me out on the streets.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her throat tightened with each word, tears forming at the edges of her eyes. The spirit wavered a moment, and then extended one of its tendrils in her direction, its ethereal contact on her shoulder conveying feelings of immense sympathy, and an understanding. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sorry. I didn’t mean to turn this into a vent about myself. I just wanted to share my own experience with you. I’m sure… I’m sure that Timothy felt the same way.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;“... tina… she said… her name was tina…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;“Tina… that’s a beautiful name.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The shadowy spirit shimmered slightly, and produced another horrid sound, that vaguely reminded Hazel of chuckling. “&lt;em&gt;iT is…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Hazel felt steel rise within her, and she pressed while the spirit was feeling the empathy. “If she were here now, do you think you could say that to her?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The spirit’s form took on more definition, like a picture coming into focus, she could see the man hiding beneath the rage and sorrow. “&lt;em&gt;yes… yes I could… I would. But… she is gone now, they all are.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Only one final thing to ask then. “Then, are you ready?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The spirit’s form finished coalescing into the more defined shape of an elderly man, his ‘back’ hunched over. “&lt;em&gt;Yes. Thank you, sweet girl, for your words. Even if I did not deserve them.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;“We all deserve peace, Spirit.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For a brief moment, Hazel saw a faint smile spread across its face. The inky blackness slowly faded away, leaving natural darkness in its wake. Hazel’s flashlight returned to its previous brightness, and the hatch opened once more. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The spirit was gone.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel let out a deep sigh, and laid down on her back as a great deal of stress rolled its way out of her body.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fuck that was exhausting…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Gathering up her thermos and the photo, the girl rose to her feet and took several careful steps down the ladder, not entirely trusting them to hold her up. After closing the hatch, she took several shaky steps down the staircase and back to Ms. Beatrice’s living room.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh! You’re back already! I take it that means the problem is solved?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel couldn’t muster up the energy for much of a response, and only nodded her head. “Yeah it’s gone… hey, uhm… I’d love to stay for those cookies, but…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The old woman looked about ready to protest, but as she got closer, her gaze narrowed ever so slightly on Hazel’s body. “It’s fine dearie, I can tell you’re exhausted. I’ll cut you a check and you can be on your way.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh right. Money. “Sure, I’ll be right here.” Ms. Beatrice went to retrieve her checkbook, and Hazel leaned against the wall, her thoughts a torrent that she was too tired to control. Though, who even uses checks these days?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel got her boots back on when Ms. Beatrice returned with a signed bankslip, protected in a plastic sheathe and handed it over to Hazel. “Here you are, thank you for your help.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah… yeah, thank you, Ms. Beatrice.” She took the check and stashed it into her leather satchel.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her smile widened, and for a brief moment, Hazel spotted cruelty. “You’re welcome sir.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Wha-&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She just.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Fear and shame shot through her body.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel turned and left immediately, not even bothering to put on her rain coat before leaving. The pouring rain soaked through her sweater immediately, and after she got the coat on, it only served to trap the moisture inside. She ran down the streets, her boots making large splashes with each step away from the inside, and back to the safety of her own apartment.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The trip back to her apartment passed by in a flash, switching from walking, to riding the train, to walking again, an elevator ride, and then back in her apartment. She slammed the door behind her, as though it could expel her torrent of thoughts.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Shame. Anger. Fear. Hurt. Betrayal.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;You’re back?”&lt;/em&gt; A wispy voice questioned, and the hazy outline of a young woman settled into place. Even in her panicked state, Hazel couldn’t help but feel a little soothed by Nina’s presence. The spirit slowly approached Hazel, and she felt her partner’s ethereal touch, full of love and concern. She tried to open her mouth and speak, but no words would come out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nina’s face twisted into greater concern, and the frown made Hazel’s heart sink. “&lt;em&gt;Oh my poor dear, are you non-verbal right now?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Hazel only nodded her head. It had been a while since it last happened, but she could not muster up words to speak right now. Nina extended a ghostly tendril towards Hazel’s head, and the witch nodded her head in consent.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nina’s face only grew more horrified as she recounted the events of Hazel’s latest job, each image being shared between them, without need for the witch to speak of them. After a few minutes, the connection severed, and Nina’s ethereal hands rested on Hazel’s head. They were incorporeal, but the sensation of shared empathy was like a soothing balm to the witch.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;Come on, let’s get you out of those clothes and into a hot shower.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Nina waved her hand, and Hazel’s clothes lifted off her, exposing the girl’s budding breasts and thin body. Her underthings remained, given how sensitive she was about those parts she had yet to fix. With a few shaky steps, Hazel stepped into the bathroom, and turned on the faucet. Hot water was a luxury item these days, but she knew better than to argue with Nina on her own needs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her shoulder length hair cascaded down from its former ponytail, and Hazel washed herself with the beeswax soap. The underground apiaries meant that sourcing it wasn’t too hard, and neither was the process for making it at home. She’d added lavender to the mix, which felt especially nice after being in a moldy attic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After spending longer than was perhaps advisable in the shower, Hazel threw on the bathrobe and her underwear before returning to the common area. Nina was there, and had prepared a steaming cup of hot tea, which Hazel graciously accepted.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“... Thank you…”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nina’s smile brightened, and the ghostly tendrils gathered once more around Hazel. Between the shower, the tea, and the presence of her girlfriend, the anxiety and fear had settled, leaving exhaustion in its place. Hazel let out a mighty yawn, and Nina giggled softly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;I prepared your bed, go take a rest once you’ve finished your tea. Don’t forget your evening pills though!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Exhausted as she was, Hazel Never forgot to take her hormones. They were hard to come by, and took up a significant chunk of her income, but it was entirely worthwhile. Especially when she could save on rent by living in an abandoned apartment and do her own repairs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A tall bookshelf lined with manuals on everything from plumbing to witchcraft was the most prominent feature of her room, and one thick tome on Enochian was sitting by her nightstand, half finished. She didn’t really feel like reading right now though.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hazel took off her robe, and fell into bed, pulling the covers up until they covered her chin. Nina flicked off the light, and crawled into the bed beside her. While her presence was intangible to the senses, Hazel strongly &lt;em&gt;felt&lt;/em&gt; her presence and settled in close against her partner.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Outside, the rain continued to steadily fall, its endless rhythm soothing Hazel into a deep slumber. It had been raining everyday for as long as she could remember, and its presence was as dear to her as Nina was.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/133722/violet_velvet/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/33/ava_133722_1725238337.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/133722/violet_velvet/"&gt;Violet_Velvet&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt; author's note: I am more afraid of being misgendered than encountering an evil spirit.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Thank you for reading this short story! It sprung nearly fully formed out of my head yesterday, and I finished editing today. I have more ideas for this setting, so there might be more short stories in the future. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Have a great day, and stay safe out there!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
